{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2243d66a-0684-466c-93d9-877c09764edf","content":"The project doesn't exist at that path in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- For a published build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` directly.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or reload the window. Copilot agent mode will discover the server and its tools automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cb14b5ad-355a-4160-aa8a-abe1ff50f357","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"CC2C:E2933:7E41C95:8C8D791:69EAC181"},"id":"66e6346c-758d-4329-a567-d879eff2c901","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:04:08.415Z","parentId":"aadb152d-5e62-477a-9c66-a7efc290d241"}
